      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Far from finding ways to make it easier to park, we should be questioning the assumption that the minority of New Yorkers who own cars have a right to clutter our streets with their personal property, free of charge.</p>
        <p>As recently as the 1950's, cars were not permitted overnight on most neighborhood streets. Those who wish to own a car in New York should either park it in a private facility or pay dearly for the privilege of housing their property on a public thoroughfare.</p>
        <p>KENNETH M. COUGHLIN  Upper West Side</p>
      </block>
